    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27.11-13_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Neihardt Collection</note>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">11</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        702 Sharp Building 
                        Kansas City 6, Mo.
                        
                        January 12, 1959
                    </dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt,</salute> 
                </opener>
                <p>I was so glad to receive your letter last Friday for I have thought about you often and I am going to drive over to Columbia in early spring or sooner to see you.</p>
                
                <p>I remembered you had a birthday on Jan. 8th and may God's peace and love rest on you as you continue to guide the lives of students. Friday evening after thinking about what you said in your letter, I played a record of your reading from "The Song of Three Friends" and it seemed as though we were in the room together, and if I closed my eyes I could see you talking to me.</p>
                
                <p>You will be pleased to know I am beginning to take the graduate courses in education to prepare myself for a teaching career. There is an unsatisfied ambition to do some-thing constructive &#8212; to contribute to 
                    
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27.11-13_0002"/>
                    
                    the well being of young people.</p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27.11-13_0003"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">12</fw>
                
                <p>It may take several years to obtain my master's degree, but I will keep at it until I do.</p>
                
                <p>I have a younger brother at John's Hopkins University, Baltimore, who hopes to obtain his doctorate in <unclear>History</unclear> this January.</p>
                
                <p>I recently corresponded with a Mr. <unclear/> Russell, editor of The <unclear>Brad</unclear> Book Chicago Corral, the Westerner's <unclear>Passe</unclear>. He asked me for a short article on your Epic America Course, and I sent him a description for use.</p>
                
                <p>While in Collinsville, Ill. recently I saw a friend Irving Dilliard. He asked me to extend his very best regards to you.</p>
                
                <p>I am not a good penman as I write by hand, but I wanted this to be a personal note, and I am looking forward to a visit with you soon.</p>
                
                <closer>
                    <salute>All the best to you,</salute>
                    <salute>your friend</salute>
                    <signed>Thomas W. Wright</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
